1455":"1455","1531":"1531","1564":"1564","1475":"1475","Abt 1490":"about 1490","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","Market Drayton, Shropshire, England":"Market Drayton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Kirton, Lincolnshire, England":"Kirton, Lincolnshire, England","Longnor Hall, Shropshire, England":"Longnor, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Somerset co, England":"Somerset, England","Carshalton, Surrey, England":"Carshalton, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Cavan, Ireland":"County Cavan, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Burton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a placename that is very common in central and northern England. The derivation in most cases is from Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fort’ (see   Burke  ) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","French (northeastern): regional variant of   Berton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Burke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Siobhan, Aileen, Brennan, Brigid, Donovan, Liam, Murphy, Ulick, Aidan, Dermot.","English and Irish (of Anglo-Norman origin): habitational name from Burgh (Castle) in Suffolk, England. <i>Burk</i> represents an Anglo-Norman pronunciation of Old English <i>burg</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘fortification’ (see   Burgh  ).","German: variant of   Burk  ."]},{"name":"Burtin","meanings":["English: variant of   Burton  .","French (eastern): regional variant of   Bertin  ."]},{"name":"Borton","meanings":["English: variant of   Burton  ."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Biblical name meaning ‘he knows’ in Hebrew, borne by a son of Onam. In modern usage, however, the name, being borne predominantly if not exclusively by girls, is more likely an altered and more obviously feminine form of   Jade   rather than a revival of the biblical name."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Joyce Burton was born in 1475, in Longnor, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard Franklin Lambert about 1490, in Carshalton, Surrey, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1531, in Market Drayton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1475–1531":"1475–1531","1455–1532":"1455–1532","1489–1549":"1489–1549","1490–1539":"1490–1539","1500–1564":"1500–1564"